        <h2 id="formation">Formation of Black Holes</h2>
        <p>
          Black holes are formed through the gravitational collapse of massive stars. 
          When a star with a mass greater than about 20 times that of our Sun exhausts its nuclear fuel, 
          it can no longer support itself against its own gravity and collapses under its own weight.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stellar Collapse:</strong> The core of the star collapses while the outer layers are blown away in a supernova explosion.</li>
          <li><strong>Singularity Formation:</strong> The core continues to collapse until it becomes a singularity, a point of infinite density.</li>
          <li><strong>Event Horizon:</strong> The boundary around the singularity from which nothing can escape, not even light.</li>
          <li><strong>Types of Formation:</strong> Black holes can also form from the direct collapse of gas clouds or through the merger of smaller black holes.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="card" aria-labelledby="types">
        <h2 id="types">Types of Black Holes</h2>
        <p>
          There are several types of black holes, each with unique characteristics and formation processes. 
          Understanding these types helps us comprehend the diversity of these cosmic phenomena.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stellar Black Holes:</strong> Formed from the collapse of massive stars, typically 5-100 times the mass of our Sun.</li>
          <li><strong>Supermassive Black Holes:</strong> Found at the centers of galaxies, with masses millions to billions of times of our Sun.</li>
          <li><strong>Intermediate Black Holes:</strong> A hypothetical class with masses between stellar and supermassive black holes.</li>
          <li><strong>Primordial Black Holes:</strong> Theoretical black holes that may have formed in the early universe shortly after the Big Bang.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="card timeline" aria-labelledby="effects">
